Transgenic mice gene signature in human colon cancer

Lin et al

10 June, 2019

true

Overview: The goals of this analysis are.

  • First, we want to know what the differences in DGE and pathways between mouse model G12D vs.G13B.
  • Second, we want to know how similar the mouse models are to its human counterpart.
    • this is either through similarity in genes or pathways.
    • we want to know if genes that are differentially expressed in the mouse models can be used to supervised clustering in humans.
    • we want to know if DGE in mouse can drive odd ratio of being in one group or another in human
    • wa want to know if DGE in mouse can predicit survival in human data.

Method

  • KRAS, NRAS and BRAF mutation analysis for TCGA: READ and COAD sets were downloaded from GDC without regards to how the mutations were called or how the samples were derived.
  • KRAS mutations
  • here is the breakdown for each mutation.
  • All samples with BRAF or NRAS will be remove, regardless of type.
  • In the plot below: mutations with a blank name means there is no a.a alteration, eg UTR

Output results explained.

  • All results are output to a single excel file called. G12D.G13D.results.xlsx
  • mouse.key ( key for mouse data )
  • pca ( An unsupervised PCA)
  • mouse.G12D ( DGE between G12D vs WT)
  • mouse.G13D ( DGE between G13D vs WT)
  • mouse.G12D.vs.G13D ( DGE between G12D vs G13D )
  • mus.gsea.compare ( GSEA found unique to each group)
  • mus.ontology.compare ( Gene ontology unique to each group)
  • mus.dge.compare ( DGE found unique for each group)
  • DGE.mouse.human ( DGE genes match by direction in both humand and mouse)
  • GSEA.mouse.human.G12D ( GSEA found in human and mouse )
  • GSEA.mouse.human.G13D ( GSEA found in human and mouse )
  • ONT.mouse.human.G12D ( Gene ontology found in human and mouse )
  • ONT.mouse.human.G13D ( Gene ontology found in human and mouse )
  • To keep the dataset harmonized I also download RNA-Seq (htseq counts) for READ and COAD from GDC as well.
  • Please note that this these are total samples NOT unique patients. Sometimes there are replicates for whatever reason. Samples are match up to Patient->Sample->Vial this is as close as I can get to match DNA to RNA counts since after vial its portion off to different experiments.
  • This corresponds to the 4th partition of the TCGA barcode.

Mice RNA-Seq

  • Mice samples raw counts were derived with RSEM using the bowtie2 aligner
  • Gene annotation and mouse genome are from genecode, GRCm38.p6 and vM18, respectively.
    • note group A146T was dropped by request.
  • Key table

  • Unsupervised PCA plot with only genes with high variance.
  • low variance is uninteresting and can infleunce downstream analysis. Removal of low varaint genes can improve downstream analysis such as dimensionality reduction and clustering. To mitigate the effect of these singls, we caluclate Coefficient of variation (CoV) for each gene and only take the top 75% of the most variant genes.

based on the above histograms these are the filters I used to define DGE.

  • these values are use to decide what filters are to be used to define DGE
    • G12D.fdr < .05
    • G12D.logfc = 1.5
    • G13D.fdr < .1
    • G13D.logfc = 1.2
    • G12D vs.G13D.logfc = 1.2
    • G12D vs.G13D.fdr < .05
  • Note that these thresholds are only recommendations, obviosly you would need to decide based on biology and other biological factors. I chose these based on how well the sets term DGE are differentiate with clustering.

Each comparison will have a total of 5 plots which will give a sense of how your data looks like after using the filters you defined earlier.

  • A scatter plot will give you a good sense of the differences between genes from each of the group: the slop of the distribution could give you an idea of how the highly expressed the genes are vs control.

  • MA plot will achieve the same but is easier to easilty spot the logFC between the group since this number is plotted as the y-axis.

  • A volcano plot will give you a good overview of both the pvalue distribution with respect to the logFC.

  • heatmap will show how well your your filters are a defining each of the groups and give you a sense of the balance between logfc.

  • we also run a PCA and also show a great seperation between the groups with 82% variance explained in dimension 1

Next we ask are DGE genes specific to mutation in mouse have an impact on human? That is, do DGEs in mouse alter the odd ratio of being in one group or another (WT vs mutation group)?

+ for example: say gene X is upregulated in GD12 mutation mouse.  We run a Logit model and show a significant odds ratio using WT as base --> GD12.  Lets say the OR is 2.6.  This sould mean that for every log2 unit increase in the gene X it is 2.6 times more likely to be in the GD12 mutant group then the WT group.  The odds of moving to a the mutant group is thus 166% ( 2.6-1) for every log2 unit increase in gene X holding all other variabels fixed, such as age. 
+ Moreover the genes that are upregulated should have increase odds of being in its respected mutation status ( that is an increase in gene expression should increase the odds of being in the mutant group) downregulated should have increase odds of being in another group. However odds ratio can be difficult to intepret this way.  Thus when looking for upregulation the base is WT and when down regulated we use the mutant group as the base, so that for example an increase OR in downregulated means an increase odds of being in the WT group as the gene expression goes up. 
+so when testing for specific genotype we dummy code every sample not associated with the mutation wt. So for example when testing for G12D, every sample that is not G12D including G13D is WT

for this logit model we also corrected for age, tumor stage and race

Taking the gene with the highest Odd Ratio DSG3. We can also run a cox hazard model to look for survival. Besides expression and mutation we also account for age, tumor stage and gender just as with the logit model above

  • We see that expression alone as well as mutation alone does not predict overall surival, however the interaction, that is expression in combination with mutation significantly increases the chance of death.

we can also go one step further and look for all gene that were upregulated in mouse; aggregate these genes and determine if high expression can account for increase in survival with or without interactions.

  • again here we split this into up and down genes.
